le, ki&Ecirc;&frac34;&Ccedil;t muxtar mayle? muxtar ya&Ecirc;&iquest;ni &Ecirc;&frac34;u&aacute;&sup1;&rsaquo;w&Ccedil;d ma&aacute;&sup1;&macr;a. kalba &Ecirc;&frac34;u-b&Ccedil;r kalba &Ecirc;&frac34;ah&Ccedil;t muxt&Atilde;&iexcl;riw&Ccedil;t la g-yaw&Ccedil;t &aacute;&sup1;&shy;&aacute;&ordm;&iexcl;ybixe la g-m&aacute;&sup1;&shy;&aacute;&ordm;&iexcl;yb&Ccedil;x&Ccedil;ttu baxta&aacute;&sup1;&macr;ux? &aacute;&sup1;&macr;a-xz&Atilde;&shy; ma brela! nura, q&Ccedil;dla ma&aacute;&sup1;&macr;a q&Ccedil;dla ma&aacute;&sup1;&macr;a! &Ecirc;&frac34;az kullu sme&Ecirc;&frac34;lu q&Ccedil;dla ma&aacute;&sup1;&macr;a. &aacute;&sup1;&macr;elu m-ma&Ecirc;&iquest;adere &aacute;&sup1;&macr;elu m-ma&aacute;&sup1;&rsaquo;&aacute;&sup1;&rsaquo;e &aacute;&sup1;&macr;elu b&Ccedil;d m&Igrave;&pound;&aacute;&ordm;&iexcl;ye tad ma&Auml;&Igrave;&pound;me duka. &Ecirc;&frac34;ega q&Ccedil;dla? ma?! &aacute;&sup1;&shy;&aacute;&ordm;&iexcl;ma he. z&Ccedil;llu tad &Aring;&iexcl;aqli m&Igrave;&pound;&aacute;&ordm;&iexcl;ye, &aacute;&sup1;&pound;-&aacute;&sup1;&pound;&aacute;&ordm;&iexcl;&aacute;&sup1;&shy;le, &aacute;&sup1;&macr;elu kutxa &aacute;&sup1;&pound;&aacute;&ordm;&iexcl;&aacute;&sup1;&shy;la b-&Ecirc;&frac34;ide tad &Ecirc;&frac34;azi n-nehra m&Igrave;&pound;&aacute;&ordm;&iexcl;l&Igrave;&pound;&aacute;&ordm;&sup1;le tad ma&Auml;&Igrave;&pound;me nura. &Ecirc;&frac34;ani x&Aring;&iexcl;ulu b&Ccedil;&Ecirc;&frac34;em&Atilde;&copy;t q&Ccedil;dla ma&aacute;&sup1;&macr;a. &aacute;&sup1;&macr;elu k-xaze &Auml;u nura lit! merdu li&aacute;&sup1;&macr;&Ccedil;n &Auml;u nura gem&Ccedil;r &aacute;&sup1;&macr;a maxz&Ccedil;nnux gem&Ccedil;r ta muxtar. &Ecirc;&frac34;ah&Ccedil;t la k-xaz&Ccedil;t. &Ecirc;&frac34;ana g-&Ccedil;mr&Ccedil;nnux &aacute;&sup1;&macr;a maxz&Ccedil;nnux! g-daw&Ccedil;qla &Ecirc;&frac34;ide g-nab&Ccedil;lle &Ecirc;&frac34;i&Aring;&iexcl; duk&Ccedil;t xrele, g-nabelle &Ecirc;&frac34;i&Aring;&iexcl; &Ecirc;&frac34;&Ccedil;xre. gem&Ccedil;r ha! k-xaz&Ccedil;t, &Ecirc;&frac34;ilaha d&Atilde;&sup3;xunile gu &Ecirc;&frac34;uxre ma&aacute;&sup1;&shy;&aacute;&raquo; ma&aacute;&sup1;&macr;a la qeda. kulla &Ecirc;&frac34;&Atilde;&iexcl;hiw&Ccedil;t &Ecirc;&frac34;a&Aring;&iexcl;em. &Ecirc;&frac34;&Ccedil;n m&aacute;&sup1;&shy;&aacute;&ordm;&iexcl;yb&Ccedil;x&Ccedil;&Igrave;twalu &aacute;&sup1;&pound;arx&Ccedil;twa &Ecirc;&frac34;&Ccedil;llu la g-eziwa hatxa. xa baxta w&Ccedil;lla ytuta &Ecirc;&frac34;axxa xri&aacute;&sup1;&macr;a. w&Ccedil;lle mpila gu &Ecirc;&frac34;uxre dida, la drela bala. m&Ccedil;n d-o yoma b&Ccedil;&Ecirc;&frac34;em&Atilde;&copy;t muxtar m&Ccedil;rre ta qa&Aring;&iexcl;a mayde gu &Ecirc;&frac34;eta baxta&aacute;&sup1;&macr;a la &Ecirc;&frac34;azi m&Ccedil;n &aacute;&sup1;&pound;alib qam-tar&Ecirc;&frac34;a &Ecirc;&frac34;&Ccedil;lla darele gu &Ecirc;&iquest;oya, darelu gu &Ecirc;&iquest;&Ccedil;bbu. la hawe mpiqa l-w&Auml;&fnof;&Igrave;riya. &Ecirc;&frac34;az n&Ccedil;xle, la k-xazele. &Ecirc;&frac34;atta x&Auml;&fnof;la&aacute;&sup1;&pound;, &aacute;&sup1;&pound;alib &Ecirc;&frac34;af&Ccedil;llu d-&Ecirc;&frac34;&Ccedil;tlu, w&Ccedil;lle gu &Ecirc;&iquest;&Ccedil;bbu la k-xazele. n&Ccedil;xle.</p>','<p>He went down, he left Amidya [and] arrived in Aradhin, Aradhin. But it was for from Amidya - day&#39;s journey, walking. It was about a day&#39;s journey. So he arrived, he went to Amidya (sic!). He rented himself a house and settled there. He settled there, but he soon realised that they were Christians [and] Christians have a cross. The woman would wear a crucifix on themselves. He saw that it was an idol. &#39;What can I do?&#39; he said, &#39;O my Lord, how can I live here? Every day I will arise and see these women [who wear] an idol around their necks! I&#39;ll have to find a way to solve, to straighten out this situation. What can we do, how can we live here?&#39; He arose, one day [when] he was walking on the road, he saw a crucifix. He saw the cross and he said, &#39;Aha! Now I&#39;ll teach them a trick or two!&#39;. There were no toilets there. We went into the countryside behind the village by the water - there was a river. There this river flowed, so there [by the] river they would sit down and do what ... What did he do? He defecated in a certain place and he stuck this crucifix in his faeces. And he came and shouted for help, &#39;Mukhtar, mukhar!&#39;, a mukhtar is the elder of a village. Do you know what a mukhtar is? Mukhtar means the village elder. &#39;You son of a bitch, you&#39;re the mukhtar! Don&#39;t you exercise discipline, don&#39;t you discipline your women? Come and see what has happened! A fire, the village is burning, the village is burning! So everyone heard &quot;the village is burning!&quot; They came with shovels, with spades, they came with water to extinguish the place [on fire]. &#39;So it&#39;s burning? What?&#39; &#39;Over there, yes.&#39; They went to fetch water, with buckets, everyone with his bucket in his hand to go to the river and fill it up and put out the fire. They thought that the village was really burning, They came and saw that there was no fire! &#39;Mirdo, there&#39;s no fire.&#39; He said, &#39;Come and I&#39;ll show you,&#39; he said to the mukhtar. &#39;You can&#39;t see. I&#39;m telling you: come and I&#39;ll show you!&#39; He took his hand and led him to the place where he had defecated, he took him to his faeces. He said, &#39;Ha! You see, your god is in excrement. How can it be that the village isn&#39;t burning? It&#39;s all your fault. If you had disciplined them, if you had shouted at them, they would not have done this. A woman sat here and defecated. It fell into her excrement [and] she didn&#39;t notice.&#39; From that day, the mukhtar told the priest to make it known in the church that women were not to walk with a cross showing but they should put it inside. They should put them inside, so that they do not come out into the open. So he had peace. Now it was over. Even though they had a cross, it was inside [and] he didn&#39;t see it. He had peace.</p>',''),(17,'Yezidis from Dohok','',76,'audio/MH 18May2005 12 - Yezidis.mp3','<span class=aramaic>ʾǝtwa gu dohok ʾēzǝdnaye. ʾani mǝn mišpaḥat newuxadneṣṣǝr wewa. g-ǝmríwalu kazdim, bas ʾắxǝni g-ǝmríwalu ʾēzǝdnaye. ʾani ʾǝ́twalu ʾilaha dohun ṣạṭạṇ wewa - ṣạṭạṇ!  xa yoma ṯele xaʾ,  ṯele l-ʿamǝdya,  xa mǝn d-anna ʾēzǝdnaye g-mzabǝnwa ṣạbun.  ʾaz ʾana šméʾwali g-ǝmri ʾilaha dohun ṣạ́ṭạṇile, ʾaz ʾana mṣọʿǝ̣ṛṛị ṣạṭạṇ. ʾawa ʾrǝqle baṯri gǝbe qaṭǝ́lwali, ʾo ʾēzǝdnaya! \n\nʾaz ʾani, ʾắxǝni k-šamʾaxwa mǝn kullu, mǝn baba l-baba, g-ǝmriwa ʾēzǝdnaye ʾǝtlu másḥafe raš t-hudaye. ʾu ʾawa qam-šaqǝ́lwale hǝnna, nǝwuxadneṣṣǝr wǝlle mǝṯya ʾǝllu.  ʾani mišpaḥa dóhunilu d-wǝllu kǝs dohuk. ʾitena maṯwaṯa ṛaba dohun.  g-ǝmri ʾǝtlu xa šex ʾuṛwa, ʾo masḥaf wǝlle kǝsle, wǝlle gu xa beṯa čuxxa la g-naqaḥ ʾǝlle.</span> \n','There were Yezidis in Dohuk.  They were from Nebuchadnezzar\'s family.  They were called Chaldees but we used to call them Yezidis.  Their god was Satan - Satan! One day, one came, he came to Amidya, one of these Yezidis, selling soap.  But I had heard that their god was Satan, so I cursed Satan.  He chased after me, he wanted to kill me, that Yezidi!\n\nNow they, we had heard from everyone, from father to son, that the Yezidis had a Black Book belonging to the Jews.  He took it, what\'s-his-name, Nebuchadnezzar brought it to them.  Those [that live] in the area of Dohuk are from his family.  There are many villages of theirs.  They say that they have a great sheikh [and] this Book is with him. It\'s in a certain house [and] no-one touches it.',''),(18,'Yezidis from Dohok','',76,'audio/SM 19May2005 1 - The Village is Burning!.mp3',NULL,NULL,NULL),(19,'Adam\'s present','',76,'audio/SM 22Aug2005 5 - Adam gives 70 years.mp3','<span class=aramaic>lazǝmwa xayewa ʾalpa šǝnne ʾaval xa yoma kullu ḍọṛọ́ṭ dǝd ʿolam dǝd hawe qam-maxzelu ʾǝlle kulla ʿolam. ʾaz xzele dawid hammelex lazǝm hawe ʾu-mayǝṯ bǝd yoma, bǝd d-o-yomǝt hawe. ṛaba qḥǝrre gemǝr ʾistadʿolam, ʾayya dawid hammelex hawe ʾu xa-u-tréʾ m-mayǝṯ? ṭamá, mǝskina? dǝ-xanča xaye halle! gemǝr hatxa la-ṃṣǝn yaʿǝnne. wǝlli xliqa hatxa lazǝm hoya. hakka ʾahi gǝbet maʾinǝtte, maʾǝnne! gemǝr ʾana maʾinǝnne.  ʾana mǝn xayi b-yawǝnne šoʾi šǝnne.  gemǝr la mpašmǝt, hạ, ʾadam.  mǝrrux, la mḅạṭḷǝtte xa-ga xǝt xabrux.  gemǝr laʾ, k-qablǝnna ʾǝlli. ʾana ʾe naqla ham ʾayya p-šoqǝtte xaye šoʾi šǝnne b-yawǝnne. mǝdraš gemǝr dān ṃṭele ʾadam ʾǝč̣ʾa ʾǝmma ʾu-šoʾí-šǝnne, lazǝm mayǝṯ čŭkun b-šoʾi šǝnne lazǝm xayewa ʾalpa šǝnne. ʾaz šoʾi šǝnne qam-yawilu ta dawid hammelex.  mp̣ọšǝmle.  ya: gemǝr ʾistadʿolam ʾana gǝben ʾalpa šǝnne xayǝn.  gemǝr laʾ, ʾod d-wǝllǝd mira. xǝleʾta naša yawǝlla la-k-xašǝx daʾǝr.  ḥắramila naša daʾǝr.  hulux xǝleʾta, lazǝm xaṛaye maqimǝtte.  mǝn-hadax ʾadam lá-xyele ʾalpa šǝnne ʾǝlla xyele ʾǝč̣ʾá-ʾǝmma ʾu-ṭḷaṯi šǝnne. ʾu-mǝtle.  ʾu-m-băṯǝr hadax hwéwale ṭḷaha bnöne, qayin, hevel ʾu-šet. xaṛaye ʾǝnoš-ži, ʾǝ́noš-ži brone wewa, k-xašwǝn ʾǝnoš.  ḥil ʾawa mǝtle,  ʾaz pǝšlu ḍọṛọ́t qǝmlu m-băṯǝr hadax hwelu naše. ʾu-ʿolam hédi-hedi hédi-hedi zǝlla, ṛẉela. </span>','He [i.e. Adam] was supposed to live for a thousand years, but one day He showed him all the generations of the world that would exist, he showed him the whole world.  So he saw that King David would be born and die on one day, on the same day that he was born.  He was very sad [and] said, \'Master of the Universe, is this King David really to be born and to die straight away?  Why?  The poor thing!  Give him a bit of life!\'  He said, \'I cannot help him like that.  I have created it thus and it must be so.  If you wish to help him, help him!\' He said, \n\'I will help him.  From my life I will give him seventy years.\' He said, \'Don\'t regret it [later], Adam.  You have said it and you cannot go back on your word later.\'  He said, \'No, I accept that.  This time, just for him, I will allow him to live.  I will give him seventy years.\'  The Midrash says that when Adam reached nine-hundred and thirty years and he was to die, for in seventy years he would have reached a thousand (but he had given seventy to King David) he regretted it.  He said, \'O Master of the Universe, I want to live for a thousand years!\' He said, \'No, do as you have said.  When one has given a present, taking it back is not allowed.  It is forbidden for one to take [it] back.  You gave a present [and] afterwards you must keep your promise.  Therefore Adam did not live for a thousand years but rather for nine-hundred and thirty years. And [then] he died.  Then there were [other] generations which arose, after this [many] people were born.  And very slowly the world developed, grew older.',''),(20,'Telkepe','A text about the village.',68,'audio/Text-TK-Khalid-30-11.mp3',NULL,NULL,NULL),(21,'Short story 1','',95,'audio/Dere Short Story 1.mp3',NULL,NULL,NULL),(22,'Short story 2','',95,'audio/Dere Short Story 2.mp3',NULL,NULL,NULL),(23,'Titta and his brothers','A folk story told to the informant by elderly neighbours in Telkepe when he was a child (partly abbreviated)',68,'audio/Titta_and_his_brothers.mp3',NULL,NULL,NULL),(24,'The story of the sparrow with the thorn in his foo','A children\'s story (versions also found in Alqosh, and among the Assyrians)',68,'audio/Butika.mp3',NULL,NULL,NULL),(25,'Story of a birth','An event in the informant\'s childhood.',50,'audio/Pesh_Story_of_a_birth.mp3',NULL,NULL,NULL),(26,'Agriculture','',50,'audio/Pesh_Agriculture_.mp3',NULL,NULL,NULL),(27,'Agriculture','',45,'audio/ShSh_Agriculture.mp3',NULL,NULL,NULL),(28,'Cheese','',45,'audio/ShSh_Cheese.mp3',NULL,NULL,NULL),(29,'Traditional medicine','',96,'audio/Narg_Trad_medicine.mp3',NULL,NULL,NULL),(30,'Bread and cheese','',49,'audio/Alq_Bread_cheese.mp3','<span class=aramaic>(28) ʾoðiwa lə́xma b-ʾàlquš.ˈ (29) qămɛ́θa ʾə́θwalɛ tănùra.ˈ ʾáθ-tănura măšəxnìwalə ʾu …ˈ m-qám mašxónəḥ măḥəð̣ṛiwa lɛ̀ša.ˈ (30) lɛ́ša m-ìlə?ˈ (31) kšáqli qàmxa,ˈ xə́ṭṭə - kúllɛ  zăṛàʾə-wɛwa,ˈ ʾə́θwālɛ xə̀ṭṭə -ˈ ṭaxníwālɛ, ʾoðíwalɛ qàmxa.ˈ (32) qámxa lɛšíwalə b-màyə-uˈ dárɛwa xmíra-mməḥ-u mə̀lxa-u …ˈ ʾu băhaṛā̀t,ˈ xákma băhaṛā̀t kəmrəxlɛ.ˈ (33) bás-kámta lā … lá-băhaṛāt də́x t-kéðila b-ʿằṛabi d-amrəx.ˈ kámta darɛ̀wa.ˈ\n\n(34) ʾoðíwa tréʾ ṭlăθa-šəkləd-lə̀xma,ˈ mənnɛy lə́xma răqìqaˈ ʾu mənnɛ́y paθxàθaˈ ʾu mənnɛ́y, ʾən măxəmíwālə rànda,ˈ ʾamriwalɛ xmìʾə-uˈ ʾóðiwa taxràθa.ˈ (35) ʾu taxráθa ʾaškā̀l-ilɛ …ˈ šə̀klə hadax:ˈ ʾáði d-gùpta;ˈ ʾəθwa mənnɛ́y s-sə̀sqə,ˈ mənnɛ́y d-ʿə̀ruq,ˈ d-gə̀rsaˈ …  ʾā́y taxràθa.ˈ\n\n(36) kúd lɛšìwalɛ,ˈ darɛwa xwána p-pàlga.ˈ (37) lɛšiwa-uˈ mqaṭṭíwalə lɛ̀ša,ˈ (38) ʾən wɛwa taxráθa-u paθxàθa,ˈ bás[z]-găròmaˈ - gàrmiwalɛ.ˈ (39) w-ən hawewa ráqqa d-lə̀xmaˈ - ráqqa … yaʿni ʾani răqìqəˈ - maxɛ́walɛ b-gèṛa.ˈ (40) géṛa qɛ́sa yărìxɛ-lə hadax;ˈ năqìða.ˈ\n\n(41) ʾu lə́xma răqíqa mṭapɛ́walə go mànzaq.ˈ (42) go mánzaq  dlà-čayəqˈ dárɛlə b-ìða,ˈ lánnăhu ṛàbə káwɛ.ˈ (43) ʾu ʾáni taxráθa-u paθxáθa hàr-b-iða;ˈ mə́nnɛy b-mànzaq,ˈ mə́nnɛy b-ìða mṭapɛ́walɛ.ˈ (44) klíθa l-bàxtɛ-la: ʾən ʾəθwaba d- … moráwa ʾíðaḥ p-tanúra dla … dlà-manzaqta.ˈ\n	\n(45) mṭapɛ́walɛ p-tanúra hawewa … mŭlə̀hyaˈ - malhɛwa ló qɛ́sa lo bàrta.ˈ (46) bárta ʾani … [B. păṭòxə.ˈ] păṭòxə yaʿni …ˈ toràθa.ˈ (47) ʾā́y wewa šărɛ̀y, məskénə;ˈ làθwalɛ.ˈ\n	\n(48) ʾā́y lə̀xma ʾu …ˈ lə́xma măpəlṭìwalə,ˈ xá-qəṣṣa răkìxa.ˈ (49) kúd paləṭwa, šăxína, taʾpìwalə;ˈ təttə̀-gaθaˈ lánnăhu mḍàwwar-wewaˈ (50) taʾpíwa ġðá-gaθa ʾaw təttə̀ʾ;ˈ payəšwa xá-məndi mθàllaθ.ˈ (51) baθə́r-dəx yawə́šwa, payəšwa -ˈ ʾarewa qàlwa hadax.ˈ (52) ṭamšíwalə b-màyə-uˈ darɛwalə p-sàllaˈ lo b- … paθàrtaˈ lo ṭabaqìyaˈ ʾamriwala táma-uˈ gðílaḥ m-qaṣàlə.ˈ (53) mkasɛ́walə xa-bɛ̀na-uˈ rakəxwa payəšwa x-pàsta.ˈ (54) ʾu taxráθa-u paθxáθa lá-rɛsiwalɛ b-màyə.ˈ (55) ʾā́y lə̀xma.ˈ\n	\n(56) dáṛəx l-gùpta,ˈ déx ʾoðíwala gùpta.ˈ (57) ʾaθéwa mzabnàna-uˈ lo ʾáni d-ə́θwalɛ ʾə̀rwə-uˈ toràθa-u …ˈ guptəd-ʾə́rwə bə̀š-bassəmtɛ-la-uˈ bə̀š-rxəšta.ˈ (58) ʾoðíwala gùpta;ˈ hoyáwa xā̀m dəx d-ámrəx:ˈ  xā̀m.ˈ lắ-wawa wə́ðta … šlə̀qta.ˈ (59) zonə́xwala gùpta-uˈ mɛθə́xwala l-bɛ̀θa;ˈ (60) ʾoðə́xwala … qɛṣə́xwala zəlpə̀-zəlpə;ˈ măṛəθxə́xwala  b-màyə,ˈ xằ-qəṣṣa.ˈ (61) kpɛ́ša x- … x-ʿallùča,ˈ x-lastìk,ˈ hádax pšə̀rta.ˈ (62) mənnɛ́y d-bás-ʾoðiwala d- … m-mə̀lxa:ˈ ʾani … báθər-ma š-šalqìla,ˈ ʾoðíwala fə̀ṣṣə …ˈ [interruption]\n\n(63) gùpta:ˈ  šalqìwala;ˈ ʾoðíwala … mə́nnaḥ p-tùma,ˈ mə́nnaḥ bás-b-mə̀lxaˈ - lá-darɛwa tùma gawaḥ.ˈ (64) túma tằri, yaʿni,ˈ lắ-tuma mən d-ani fə̀ṣṣə.ˈ [B. yărùqə.ˈ] yărùqə d-amrəx,ˈ ʾè.ˈ (65) băθə́r-dəx šaqlìwala,ˈ daʿkíwala b-ìðaˈ mṣănəṣlíwalɛ màyaḥ.ˈ ʿaṣrìwala,ˈ máyaḥ palṭìwa.ˈ (66) darɛ́wa túma p-pàlgaḥ,ˈ ʾu dabqíwala l-ə̀ġðaðəˈ - wola x-kŭbàbta.ˈ (67) darɛ́wala b-mə̀lxa;ˈ darɛ́wala p-qóqa lo p-sànda.ˈ (68) ʾu darɛ́wa máyə [interruption] máyə-u mə̀lxa,ˈ r-rešɛ̀yˈ ʾìman t-qɛṛáwa.ˈ (69) darɛwa máyə-u mə́lxa r-rešɛ̀y-uˈ (70) darɛwa ġðá-ṭapšə̀kθa,ˈ párčəd- … [B. faràšta.ˈ] făràšta ʾamriwala,ˈ t-ḥắṣu  … bṭə̀xta,ˈ ta t-páyəš yùqra r-réšaḥ,ˈ wə́l n-naxθàwa,ˈ xu máyə-u mə̀lxa-uˈ ʾu ʾàxliwa.ˈ</span>','(28) They used to make bread in Alqosh. (29) Before, they used to have an oven. This oven they heated and before heating it they prepared lεša {dough}. (30) Lεša, what is it? (31) They take flour, wheat – all of them were farmers, they had wheat – they milled it, they made it into flour. (32) The flour they kneaded with water, and they put yeast with it and salt and bahārāt {spices} , some bahārāt (as) we call them. (33) Just kamta , not bahārāt as they know them in Arabic, I\'d say.  They added kamta.\n\n(34) They made two or three types of bread, among them \'fine bread\' and among them paθxāθa {large thin pitta breads} and among them, if they leavened it well, (what) they called \'leavened\'; and they made taxrāθa {small thick pitta breads}. (35) And taxrāθa come in different kinds  … kinds like this: cheese-bread ; there was among them sheep\'s-tail-fat-bread, among them >eruq -bread, cracked-wheat-bread … That\'s taxrāθa.\n\n(36) When they kneaded them, they put a xwāna {low round table} in the middle. (37) They kneaded and pinched off the dough. (38) If they were taxrāθa and paθxāθa, just a rolling-pin – they rolled them out. (39) And if it was a raqqa {thin piece} of bread – a raqqa, that is, the thin ones – they rolled it  with a gēra {fine rolling pin}. (40) A gēra is a long piece of wood like this; thin.\n\n(41) And the fine bread they stuck (inside the oven) with the oven-cushion. (42) With the oven-cushion so that it doesn\'t tear, so that they may hold it with the hand, because they are large. (43) And these, taxrāθa and paθxāθa, are just with the hand; some of them with an oven-cushion, some of them they stuck them with the hand. (44) It depends on the woman: if she could put her hand into the oven without an oven-cushion.\n\n(45) They stuck them inside an oven which had been lit – they lit either wood or sheep-dung. (46) Sheep-dung, these … [B. Cow dung.] cow-dung, I mean … Cows. (47) This was their fuel, the poor; they didn\'t have (anything else).\n\n(48) That\'s bread … The bread they brought out, a little soft. (49) When it came out, hot, they folded it, twice because it was circular. (50) They folded once or twice; it became something triangular. (51) «...» Afterwards it dried and became – took a shape, like this. (52) They dipped it in water and put it in a basket or in a paθarta-basket or a ṭabaqiya {wicker tray}, (as) they called it there, woven from straws. (53) They covered it for a while and it softened and became like cloth. (54) Taxrāθa and paθxāθa they did not sprinkle with water. (55) That\'s bread.\n\n(56) Let us return to cheese, how they made the cheese. (57) There used to come a seller or those who had sheep and cows … Sheep\'s cheese is nicer and more common. (58) They made the cheese; it was unprocessed, as we say: \'unprocessed\'. It was not made … boiled. (59) We bought the cheese and took it home; (60) we made it … we cut it into slices; we boiled it in water, a little. (61) It becomes like … like chewing gum,  like elastic, melted like that. (62) (There were) some who just made it with salt. These … after they boiled it, they made it into segments. [interruption]\n\n(63) Cheese: they boiled it; they made some of it  with garlic and some of it just with salt – they didn\'t put garlic in it. (64) Fresh garlic, I mean, not garlic from these cloves. [B. Green.] Green, as we say,  yes. (65) After that they took it, they pressed it by hand, they made its water drip out. They squeezed it, its water came out. (66) They put garlic in the middle of it, and they stuck it together – it\'s like a kubba.  (67) They put it in salt; they put it in a small pot or a big pot. (68) And they put bri- [interruption] brine,  on top of them, when it cooled down. (69) They put brine on top of them (70) and they put a flat-stone, a piece of … [A pebble. ] a pebble they called it, of pebble, flat, to be a weight on top of it, until it would go down, under the brine … And they ate.',''),(31,'The village of Peshabur','',50,'audio/Pesh_Peshabur_adib.mp3',NULL,NULL,NULL),(32,'Burghul wheat','',50,'audio/Pesh_gurgur_adib.mp3',NULL,NULL,NULL),(33,'Marriage_1','',96,'audio/Narg_Marriage1.mp3',NULL,NULL,NULL),(34,'Marriage_2','',96,'audio/Narg_Marriage2.mp3',NULL,NULL,NULL),(35,'Life in Darband','',93,'audio/Life_in_Darband-c.mp3',NULL,NULL,NULL),(36,'Spinning and weaving','',96,'audio/Narg_Spinning_and_Weaving.mp3',NULL,NULL,NULL),(37,'Christmas and Easter','',27,'audio/Billin, Christmas and Easter.mp3',NULL,NULL,NULL),(39,'Life in Ankawa','',26,'audio/Ankawa 17.02.06, life in Ankawa.mp3',NULL,NULL,NULL),(40,'Derabun, the people and the dialect','',25,'audio/Derabun, the people and the dialect (17.11.05).mp3',NULL,NULL,NULL),(41,'Aradhin and its people','',23,'audio/Aradhin 4.11.04 1, Aradhin and its people.mp3',NULL,NULL,NULL),(42,'Bread','',25,'audio/Derabun, bread (17.11.05).mp3',NULL,NULL,NULL),(43,'Building houses','',25,'audio/Derabun, building houses (17.11.05).mp3',NULL,NULL,NULL),(45,'Children s