g-yatwíwa g-ozíwa láxma raqìqa,| \nšoʾá tmanyá baxtàsa.|\ng-yatwíwa,| u-g-ozíwa láxma ràqiqa.| xá g-e[w]ə́zwalu hàdxa| xá bə́ž rùwwe,| xá bə́ž rùwwe,| ʾə́d lá mə̀lxa.|\ng-ozíwā̄,| má ʾamrànax| tre ṭḷ[áh]a guníyye kúd ᴴməšpaḥà.ᴴ| \ng-jamʿíwa| g-ozíwa láxma raqíqa ta tmanyá yòme.|\nᴴʾazᴴ ʾə́swa ʾə̀rxe| də́d məšəlmàne wéla,| ʾavál ta ᴴpèsaḥ,ᴴ| m-qábel ᴴpésaḥ,ᴴ| tré šabàsa| ṭḷàha,| g-ozíwala, ʿaġàla,| \nu...| u-k-taxníwa qàmxa ʾáxnan,| k-taxnáxwa qàmxa l-tám.| e xə́ṭṭe gə-mxalìwala,| u-g-mawišìwala.| \nžnít g-ezíwa ʾel e hə̀nna,| ʾəl ṭaḥùne,| g-taxnìwala.| žnít k-séwa g-yapèwa.|\nʾè wéla,| ᴴbètaḥ.ᴴ|\nBA: ᴴʾázᴴ ʾə̀rxe| ᴴmexonát tḥìnaᴴ híla?| \nZBN: hé,| ᴴmexonát tḥína,ᴴ k-taxnàwā̄,| ʿolám qámxe u-mə́ndi k-taxnàwa.| \nBA: ʾatta-kúd k-palə̀xwa,| kúllu pàre| g-meséwalu tá... xmàse?|\nZBN: hè,| hè,| kúllu ᴴyàḥadᴴ wélu.|\nmád yawáwalu xmàsu,| ʾáya wèla.| ʾáni lá-g-naḥqíwa ʾəl čú-mə̀ndi.| kalása, làʾ!|\nkúllu k-palxíwa ᴴyàḥad,ᴴ| u-kúllu xmása u-xəmyàna wélu.|\nʾəbéwa xà-məndi,| xmása b-amráwa, hàllula.| \nxá mə́ndi zonàwa,| g-əbéwa xmása mʿamràwa.|\nBA: ṃáṭo xá məndí...?\nZBN: ᴴmàšehu nagíd rot͡sá liknót...ᴴ \nBA: ᴴló!ᴴ sqíla mə̀rax,| xá-məndi g-əbàwa,...?\nZBN: xá-məndi ʾebàwa,| xmása gə-nheláwa [gə-hənna-wa?] ṭáḷa qavʿàwa.|\nlá-mṣáwa mnóša zonáwa čù-məndi.|\nBA: wáy wáy wày,|\nZBN: hílla xmàsa,| ʾamráwa hè,| ʾàya wéla.| ','ZBN: That is how it was. Everybody [lit. all of them] together [lit. in together].\nWe were neighbors. Arabs, Muslims.\nThere were no taps. No one had [lit. all of them did not have] water taps.\nBA: How many rooms did you have?\nZBN: We had four-five rooms. Each one [of them] was like a room [=each room was separate]. Whoever got married had his own room [lit. each (one who) married was in one room].\nAfter all, all of the family used to live [lit. be] together. \nDaughters in law, his sons in law,...\n...\nYou used to live in one, eh, [in] the Kurdish neighborhood [in Jerusalem], one, there was [only] one room. Ten persons used to sleep in that room.\nBA: Right,\nZBN: And guests used to come and they have [also] had place.\nBut the house of the family of my father [back in Zakho] was large.\nVery large it was.\nLook, it was joyous there [lit. joy was there].\nEh, and all were one hand [=cooperating, mutually helping]. Everyone [lit. all of them] was helping one another. \nEh, everyone, for instance the neighborhood of Kurds [=Kurdish Jews] that was [there], [that neighborhood] of ours. [or: the neighborhood of our Kurds (=Kurdish Jews) that was (there)],... \nA wedding - they used to hold each wedding for eight days [lit. eight days they used to make a wedding].\n[On] a certain [lit. one] day they would ask for her hand,\nand [on another] day they would say [=plan, decide], [today is the day we] should [perform the ritual of] informing her [about her future marriage, lit. make her hear].\nAnd they used to hold [lit. make] a [ceremonial] Shabbat, before the wedding they would hold [lit. make] a [ceremonial] Shabbat.\nThey would carry a metal tray [with jewellery henna and the bride price] , and with Dola and Zurne  they would go to the parents of the bride. \nAnd another [lit. one] night they would do Henna, until the morning. And... \nAnd one night they would say [=decide that this night will be],\na Between.\nMeaning between Henna and this, a break of one day.\nAnd... I know? [=What else can I tell] our customs, [the customs] of the Kurds [=Kurdish Jews]. And... \nBA: You were married here,\nZBN: I [was married] here, yes.\nAnd afterwards they would put the bride on a horse.\nBA: Oh...\nZBN: On top of a horse, a horse.\nBA: And they would take her to the house of the family of the groom?\nZBN: Yes, they would take her [and] put her in a [???], on top of this,\nhorse.\nAnd they would dress her up in bride\'s clothes.\nA shirt and a robe, and a vest, and covered [lit. filled] with gold, and a turban on her head.   \nAnd they would grab her two-two [=in pairs] [and] lift her [and] put her on the horse. \nAnd each one would hold her on one side, [and] they would hold [firm] the horse,... \nBA: Oh!...\nZBN: ...and they would take her to the groom\'s house. Sure.\nBA: Gule, Gule was born here? Um, was married here or was she married in Zakho?\nZBN: My sister Gule was married in Zakho!\nBA: Oh, in Zakho,\nZBN: She married her husband in Zakho, yes.\nThere has not been a [wedding] hall,  what hall has there been [in Zakho]? So she [the bride], they would take her to his [the groom\'s] family house. All of the girls and the women gathered around the bride,\nand the groom would sit with the men.\nAfter that, [for] seven days,\nthey would not permit her to do anything [any domestic work].\nBA: [They would celebrate with] Dola and Zurne, \nZBN: It was Dola and Zurne, playing every day [lit. every day pounding]. \nAnd they would not let the bride do anything, nothing, nothing, [they would not let her] touch any thing.\nUp until eight days afterwards. Eight days afterwards she would work hard... \nHard labour...\nBA: Yes, hard labour, yes,\nZBN: She would do difficult work.\nYes.\nBA: Whoever got married lived at her father in law\'s house [?]\nZBN: [Yes] her father in law\'s house. They all lived together.\nEach family was, was about ten families [living] in one house.\nThere were very large houses. And a courtyard [for each house] and rooms all around it.\nAnd each one [=each nuclear family] had his room [lit. and each one and his room].\nAnd at night[s] they would go up [on their beds] and in the day[s] everyone went [out and work] together.\nOne would do the laundry, and one would cook, and one would sew. And one would go [and] bring water. What? \nBA: When the mother in law quarrelled with the daughter in law, what would they do?\nZBN: Wi!\n[It has been] one mess, there would be a fight, the mother in law would fight with the daughter in law, she [the mother] would spark a dispute between her [the daughter in law] and her husband.\nThey would make a mess, a fight. And there [in Zakho] the mother in law was this,\nBA: the person who made the decisions.\nZBN: the person who made the decisions.\nWhatever the mother in law would say, that was it.\nThat was that.\n[Whenever] she said \'eat now\', they would eat,\n[whenever] she told them \'do not eat now\', they would not eat.\n\'You should bake, launder\'.\n[Whenever] this, the Festivals came,\neh... Passover,\nEveryone, before Passover,\ntwo [or] three weeks [before],\nused to go to the river. It is called [lit. they say to it]\nthe stream, eh...\nthe stream of the old Christian neighborhood of Zakho.  It was like,\nlike in the mountain[s]. It was not a large sea, it was like a [small] brook.\nThey would go,\n[and] make laundry there, they would wash the blankets, the carpets,  \nmattresses, they would wash all of them, put them in the water, wash them.\nThey would put them on the rocks,\nuntil they were dried.\nAnd after they would dry, they would fold all of them, poor [women]. \nAnd they would put them on a donkey and come back [to town] [very late] in the evening. Their tongue longer than their feet.\nBA: Exhausted, yes,\nZBN: for Passover.\nBut, Passover was indeed Passover [back] in Iraq. It was not like [it is] here.\nOne month, two months before Passover, they used to sit [and] make thin bread.  \nseven [or] eight women.\nThey would sit and make thin bread. One would make them [the units of bread] as [big as] that. One, bigger. One, [even] bigger. Without salt.\nThey would make, what shall I tell you, two [or] three sacks [for] each family.\nThey would gather [and] prepare thin bread for eight day [the eight days of Passover].\nSo, there was a mill, it belonged to Muslims [lit. of Muslims it was], but for Passover, before Passover, two [or] three weeks, they would kosher it for Passover [lit. do _ag_a_la (=Heb. hag_ala) to it]. \nAnd they would mill flour, we would mill flour there. Eh, They would wash the wheat and dry it.\nOnly then they would go to eh this, to the mill, [and] mill it. And then they would come [bake] and bake. \nThis [is how it] was, sure.\nBA: So ___rxe is a milling machine?\nZBN: Yes, milling machine, it used to mill... abundance [lit. Heb. world] of flours and things it used to mill.  \nBA: Now, whoever worked, would bring all the money to... the mother in law?\nZBN: Yes, yes, everyone was together. \nWhatever the mother in law would give them, that was it. They [the daughters in law] would not touch a thing. Daughters in law, no!\nEveryone would work together, and all of it was [for] the mother and father in law [or: and all was the mother and father in law. =they were the decisive factor in all things].\n[When someone] wanted something, the mother in law would say, give it to her.\n[If] she [=one of the daughters in law] would buy anything, the mother in law felt compelled [lit. there was a need] to boss around and criticize her. \nBA: How [did you say it?], [if she would buy] anything...?\nZBN: Let\'s say she wants to buy anything...\nBA: No! You said in nicely, [if] she wanted something,...?\nZBN: [If] she wanted anything, the mother in law would manage her [and] decide for her [or: the mother in law would this to her, decide].\nShe could not buy anything by herself.\nBA: Way way way.\nZBN: Until she, the mother in law, would say yes, that was it.\n',''),(172,'Traveling Merchants','Yitzhak Zizi tells about his experiences as a peddler in the mountains of Kurdistan.',78,'audio/Travelling Merchants.mp3','<span class=aramaic>IZ: ᴴʾazᴴ ʾó ᴴməsḥárᴴ wèle,| \nBA: wa-ʾáhet g-ezə́twa məd bàbox?| \nIZ: bằle,| ʾána ᴴʿozérᴴ díde wèli u-ʾána káteb wèli,| kaswə̀nwa ši.| \nBA: hé hè,| \nIZ: g-emə́rwa-li ʾanya-kmá ʾúzlu? g-ə́mri ʾúzlu ʾàsqadda.| ksú šə́mmed ʾáḥmad bər ḥàsan,| ʾásqad šqèlle| ʾásqad hŭ̀lle| ʾásqad pà[y]eš.| ʾóha ᴴdáfᴴ| ʾóha ʾé waráqa dìde híla.|\nxá-yoma mṭélan ʾəl xa-mása g-əmríla məšàra.| məšàra,| ʾánya lá-g-loši šála-šapə̀qsa,| ʾánya g-lóši,| fəstàna| u-sáko rèša.| múx ᴴsaʿùdim.ᴴ| kafíyya ʿagála.| mṭélan tàma,| wáʿad gùbta