| bəd kùrdi,| u-lá-k-iʾìluwa,| u-ʾáni-g-paqʾíwa mən-gə̀xka.| \nsélan kəslòhun,| g-émer ʾána g-manə̀nnu,| mə́rri mnìlu.| qam-manàxlu,| ksúli mléle ksùli,| mpə́qlu| ᴴbe-ʿérexᴴ tré ʾálpe u-qəṣùr,| banqanòt.| g-ér tré ʾálpe u-qəṣúr kmá hìlu?| mə́rri ʾe tré ʾàlpe,| ᴴbe-ʿérexᴴ g-òzi,| ʾárbi - ʾárbi u-tré diṇàre.| má[at] b-imàra?!| mə́rrile bā̀bo,| ʾáya wèla.| ʾásqad híla banqnót go zàxo.| mən ʾásqad b-ʾásqad darə̀tte| péši ʾárbi u-trè,| \nBA: ʾó-weala| ʾó-weale páre də́d| tùrkiya wéale?| \nIZ: tŭ̀rkiya,| banqanót g-əmríwale qamàe,| xaráe pə́šle lìra.| \nBA: hè,| \nIZ: ʾána húllan ṭḷáha dináre u-pàlge.| ʾə́tlan ʾáxxa ʾárbi u-trè dináre.| \nBA: k-sÉ™Ì€blan.| \nIZ: ksába - ksába ᴴgadòlᴴ wéla,| mạ́ṭo b-ʿéši šóʾa-asar-yalùnke?| \nBA: ᴴnaxòn,ᴴ|\nIZ: tré baxtàsa,| ʾu-kḗlu ʾàrxe?| \nBA: ᴴkól ha-kavòd,ᴴ| \nIZ: ʾárxe dəd k-ése mən gundə́kat, k-ése kəslèni ʾéka b-àzi?| \nBA: hé hé ᴴbètaḥ.| kèn.ᴴ| \nIZ: ʾána xḷə̀sli?| ᴴ tòv,| le-ḥayèxaᴴ| \nBA: ᴴli-briʾùtᴴ|','IZ: So that [is how] commerce was, \nBA: And you were going [along] with your father? \nIZ: Of course, I was his helper and I was the scribe [bookkeeper], I also used to write. \nBA: Yes, yes, \nIZ: He used to tell me \'Those [people], how much did they do?\' \'They say they have done so and so.\' \'Write down the name of Aḥmad son of Ḥasan, so and so [merchandise] he took, so and so [money] he gave, so and so remains [to be paid]\'. This page, this piece of paper is his.\nOne day we arrived at a certain village named [lit. they say (to) it] MÉ™Å¡ara. [The people of] MÉ™Å¡ara, they [lit. those] do not wear Å ala [and] Å pÉ™qsa, they [lit. those] wear, a [full length] gown and a jacket above it. Like the Saudis. Kafiyya [and] Agalla. We have arrived there, it is WaÊ¿ad Gubta [=The Time of Cheese]. \nWhat is Waʿad Gubta? It is [in the] spring, bahar is spring. It is the time of spring, we came there they say \'Ah! Welcome welcome! [lit. you came into our eyes] ! All of our milk - we don\'t know what we shall do with it. There is a lot of milk, go ahead take [some], as much as you take make [out of it] cheese for yourself, afterwards we shall do the account. [If] you have anything give us, [if] you do not have what can we do. \nThose [people] - so mindless were they, they would not go to Zakho taking their merchandise [in order to] sell it. They do not know where is Zakho, slime soiled their head [contemptuous curse]. \nBA: They would wait for you [to come], yes, \nIZ: This was the story. Good, we put the cheese there, evening had come, two persons came. Two people came, they say \'Is there a merchant here? A merchant [that] sells cloths?\' They say \'Yes\'. He says \'We have heard, we came [through] mountain trails [?, should be dos sarre],  they say he is in Məshara. We have come here to Məshara we heard he that he was here.\' Well, Le-Hayyim [=Cheers. IZ drinks] \nBA: Le-Hayyim! To your Health! \nIZ: Why don\'t you drink? Drink this like that, slowly slowly,\nBA: No, I don\'t drink beer.\nBA: It is so pleasant here, \nIZ: Thank God, \nBA: Garden of Eden!\nIZ: Well, what shall I tell you xuÅ¡kamÉ™Ì†ne, do you know what is xuÅ¡kamÉ™Ì†ne? \nBA: No, \nIZ: My dear sister, \nBA: Oh, nice, \nIZ: Yes, what shall I tell you xuškamə̆ne, they tell him \'Jew,\' he says \'What?\', he says \'We are qačaxe,\' What is qačaxe?\nBA: Middlemen, \nIZ: Bandits. \nBA: qačax? No, when... \nIZ: qačaxe, qačax \nBA: qačax, \nIZ: Bandits! \nBA: Bandits, \nIZ: \'We are bandits, we have come from Tayaʾa, from Turkey [lit. from the side of Tayaʾa, the side of Turkey], from the places of Kurdistan in Turkey [=the Kurdish areas of Turkey]. Indeed we have done, we have robbed [some] money, we made a robbery\'. - How is it called [lit. what they say to it]? nahibe, robbery, we robbed\'. \nBA: Robbery, we robbed [some] money, \nIZ: \'We have robbed a [certain] place, we took what they had, we put all of it in that bag. The bag was filled with papers [=banknotes]. We do not know how much is here. That bag, take it for yourself. Give cloths to us, for me, and for my daughter, and for my wife, and for my other daughter, and for his other daughter, the same, also for him [lit. that MS] give, for his wife and for his daughter, we want all of it [to be] č̣ap̣òn\'. None, no čiti [=light painted or printed cotton cloth ], no flowers, no nothing. Those [people] do not wear [these cloths], they dress only in order to [decently] cover themselves, čapòn. \nOA: What is čapòn? \nIZ: čapòn is white cloth. There is brown white cloth, [and] there is white white cloth, called [lit. they say to it] xəzna. \nBA: xÉ™zna, yes, \nIZ: White white [cloth] is xÉ™zna. \nBA: Yes, true, \nIZ: čapòn, that\'s thicker, and more brown, more beige. Do you understand? \nOA: From what [is it made]? They would make it out of cotton? \nIZ: Out of cotton, every thing out of cotton, yes.\nMy father says \'What shall we do?\' I said \'What [do you mean], father, we do not have a choice. We cannot do anything [lit. we do not have anything to do]. We must to give them [whatever they want]. They are naked.  We do not know [lit. what do we know] what is there in those paper[s]. We do not know how much those papers are worth [lit. papers, of what papers we do not know]. Comply with their demands [lit. give them their rightful price], [in order that] they should leave. If we do not give them, \nBA: They would kill you, \nIZ: They will come [and] wait in front of us and in one place they will execute their murderousness upon us [lit. kill themselves upon us].  He tells me \'Indeed you speak truth\', he says \'Bring a bolt of fabric\'. I placed [lit. seated] [the bolt], and he measured and measured and measured so [and] so [and] so [and] so. The bolt - I bought it myself for three and a half Dinars, by credit.\nI brought it, he says \'The bolt is finished, the thing is finished, three and a half Dinars were wasted [lit. went away]\'. He says \'Let them [the Dinars] go away, let them go away, God [lit. (may I be the) sacrifice of God] will give [=provide]. We shall see what, in any case there must be something in that [lit. that this] bag.\nBA: Yes,\nIZ: Three Dinars and a half were lost [lit. went away], oh boy! My father became a little sad. Ḥaji Aḥmad rose [and] said [lit. says] to him: \'Saleḥ, do not fear, do not be sorry, if you have lost anything [lit. from what you missed] - I will pay you back\'.\nThey also [the villagers]. They came back, they saw something [was] not right. They tell him: \'Jew, by your head Jew, by the head of our children, take this bag, take it away, from now [on] we know you have lost [money] with us [=in our village]. But we will not leave it [the injustice done to you] upon ourselves, we will not leave it [=we will make sure you will receive compensation]. God will have mercy [Heb.], God will have mercy [Kurmanji]. God knows, He is before [lit. above/on] our eyes\'. Good.\nThe landlord came, the owner of the house, he says: \'Go ahead, take yourself, go [lit. come] [and] descend [toward] Sorya [Syria?]. Near the water, the Great Water [=beside the route of the river]\'. Do you know what is the Great Water? \nBA: Yes, the Great River,\nIZ: The Great River. Where a great river [or: the Great River] flows down. \'Go [lit. come] near the water [or: by the water\'s route] of Sorya [Syria?], to the house of Moḥammad ʿAli. What a dear man he was, Oh boy! He had a wife, her name was [lit. they call her] Ḥalibe. She loved me! She used to dance whenever I arrived, because I used to make her laugh. I used to tell them, I used to tell them stories, in Kurdish, and I did not know [that language well], and they would burst out laughing [lit. out of laughter].\nWe arrived at them [=their house]. He [father] says: \'I shall count them\' I said \'Count them\'. We counted them, I wrote [down], he counted, I wrote [down], they came out [=the sum was], approximately two thousand and [some] change, banknotes. He says: \'Two thousand and [some] change how much are they?\' I said: \'These two thousand, more or less make [=worth] forty, forty two Dinars\'. \'What are you saying?!\' I said to him: \'Dad, that is what it is. Such is [the value] of banknotes in Zakho. [If] you put [=convert] this [amount] into this, it becomes forty two. \nBA: This was money of Turkey?\nIZ: Turkey, banqanot they used to call it before, afterward it became Lira.\nBA: Yes,\nIZ: I, we gave [=spend] three and a half Dinars. We have here forty two Dinars.\nBA: We made a good profit.\nIZ: [The] profit - was a large profit. How can one feed seventeen children?\nBA: True,\nIZ: Two wives, and what about [lit. where are] the guests?\nBA: Well done!\nIZ: Guests who come from the villages, they come to [stay with] us, where would they go?\nBA: Yes yes sure. Yes.\nIZ: Did I finish? Good, cheers [lit. to your life]!\nBA: To [your good] health\n',''),(173,'The Lazy Boy and the King\'s Daughter','Told by Samra Zaqen. A folktale about a young princess, banished from the palace, who disciplines a lazy young man. ',78,'audio/The Lazy Boy and the King\'s Daughter.mp3','<span class=aramaic>SZ: ʾàz| ʾə́swa xá márre tèʾna| - ʾo-ᴴbaḥúrᴴ dəd téʾna maḥkyànnalox,| há wet šmìʾa dída ᴴkanərʾéᴴ?| \nBA: làʾ|\nSZ: ʾə́swa xa-ᴴbaḥúrᴴ, ᴴméʾod méʾod yafèᴴ-wele.| (u) ᴴmuxšàr,| ṭòv,| yafèᴴ.| kúllu ʿálam g-žàġli| u-mpárnəsi gyànu,| g-ózi šoʾàle.| \nawa g-er la, la g-bewa. bábe yímme mjozèlu| mən maḥkòye| kappàrox| si žġòl| d-gòret| dəd yàtwet| did haʾ…, ma p áwe bəd-bèsa?!| mà-lox?!| la g žàġlen g-ér.| la g žàġəl ʿaṣlán.| là g-žáġel,| \nBA: kaslÃ n|, \nSZ: hḕ|, ʿaṣlán-kaṣlàn| hile-dmìxe xe-téʾna.|\nʾèha,| ḥakóme d-áy bàžer,| ʾə́tla ṭḷahá bnàsa.| mutwíle kút-ṭḷahùn| g-émer sàun| bǹasi,| máni bə́ž g-əbèli?| \nʾay-rábsa g-ə́mra bàbi,| g-əbánnox qčín mə́lkəd dùnye,| kmá g-əbánne ʾe-bohəráet-dùnye,| ʾáhet g-əbánnox ʾòṭo,| - g-əbàtti|. \nʾay-xét g-érra bráti kmá-g-əbàtti?| g-əmrá mád-mə́rra xàsi.| qčín bohoráet ʾèni| u-ᴴbriyútᴴ dídi g-bànnox.| \ng-ér ʾáy trè.| məséle ʾay-zùrta,| bráti ʾā́[ha]t kmá g-əbàtti?| g-ə̀mra| bàbi| g-əbànnox| qčín mə́lxa dəd-g-dáre ʾəl qə̀zra ṃáṭo p̣-óya basə́mta ʾ̣ọ́ṭọ g-əbànnox.| \nowà!| mux-mə́lxa g-əbátti bàs?!| g-er-ʾáhat lá-g-nafʾat ṭàḷi,| šqól čáṇṭa dídax u-sè.| la-g-yawə́nnax čù-məndi.| ʾánya tré bnási-lu, ʾáhat léat-bràti,| wí!| \ngə́mra ᴴbəsséder ā́băᴴ,| ᴴmá-še-ʾattá ʾamárta,ᴴ màši.| mád-g-ə́mret,| ᴴʾaní mekabèlet.ᴴ| \nha-ʾáya wèla.| ʾé šqə́la| čánṭa dída èka báza?| ʾəla-daw-ᴴkéremᴴ dəd-bàba.| ʾə́tle ᴴkéremᴴ rùwwa,| g-əmra bán yátwan tàma| b-ozánni xa-ᴴpinnà.ᴴ| k-xázyan híl dóqan gyàni,| má ʾòzan má la-ʾozàn.| \ng-èza| k-xàzya,| wéla čánṭa ʾə̀mma,| k-xázya xá ᴴbaḥùr,ᴴ| - sqìla,| jəndàya,| ᴴbaḥùr,ᴴ| - wéle šṭíḥa xe-tèʾna.| ḥā́àd| maxyále hənna, pehne, ᴴqúm qúm mà-atta…ᴴ| qày wet-dmíxa ʾàxxa?!| ᴴló matʾím lexá baḥúr yáfe,ᴴ jəndàya,| qày wet-tíwa xé-tèʾna?!| \ng-ḕmer| ā́na| lebi ʾozen tèʾne,| gó nàpla xá go-pə̀mmi baxlə̀nna.| \nqá qlòʿ!, g-əmrále, qlòʿ!| téʾne nápla go-pə̀mme| b-ā́xə̀lla!| g-emə́rra| háwa-má b-daryát-bi ha[ware],| g-ə́mra b-daryàn-box hawàre!| qu-l-ʾàqle, qu-l-ʾáqle, átta!|\nlaxwa hằʾ ʾahá b-šáqlan šə́ffet ʿarṃóṭa u-b-àsyan ʾə̀llox!| zə́lla nčə́lla šəffet ʿarṃóṭa, tràq!| mxéla  l-ʾàqlase.| \nmurə̀mle ʾáqle,| mùrəmle ʾáqle,| xái-ṭàlax mà-g-əbát?| g-er-mà-g-əbán?| ána brát-ḥakóma wán kpə̀nta.| g-ə́ban áhet-zonétti ʾixàla,| avál b-ǧàġlet!| ʾózet ʾarbà qrúše| ʾózet ṭḷàha qrùše,| zonéttu-li píta u-màd-sèle,| mesə́tti ʾixàla.| \nxáy ṭàlax| ána lén žġìla,| ána lá k-íʾen zònen| lá k-íʾen žàġlen,| gə́mra lá g-bàrya!| \nʾərə̀qle| zə̀lle,| zə́lle l-šùq| xáy ṭálox ta-dó-g-er čánṭa dídox hálile, háli xá qùruš.| \nxáy ṭálox ó hə́nna dídox b-šaqlànne,| b-ozánnox xá šùla| háli xá, xá šilìn.| xá tré šīlíne ʾùzle,| trè,| zəlle hiwile b-xa-zwaʾta u, - mád mése g-ə̀ba,| - hiwíle b-xá kád ṃàỵa| u-xápča zwàʾte| u-msèle-la.| mə́rra ᴴpsèder,ᴴ| ʾə́dyo ʾànwa| bə́ne bə̀š-tov.| \nysá-tu ʾaxlax,| xə̀lle,| qə́mla g-əmrà| de-qù| šqól hə̀nna,| jəʾóza, qtóʾ ṭàrpe,| u-máttu ʾáxxa ʾóz xá ᴴmìta,ᴴ| xa-ṭàli| xa-ṭàlox,| b-dámxax, ʾèka b-dámxax?| \nʾuzlu ṭàrpe| ʾ