əṭe ʾaxxa, \nlat-lan baban qam-Å¡adÉ™rran. \nʾaz ʾe, k-iʾitula ḥəkosa dohun, \nxa naqla ʾuzlelun ᴴʾauḥa,ᴴ \nhay ʾar ʾay naqla qamesa, \nṃaṭo d-ʾərru g-emer tre, \ng-emer ʾəšta bnone did ē leʾa, yatwi axxa, \nʾuzleleu ᴴšulḥàn.ᴴ \nBA: he, \nSZ: tre dĭd bilha, tamaha. \ntre dĭd ē... \nBA: zÉ™lpa? \nSZ: zilpa tamaha. \nʾuzlelu ᴴšulḥanot.ᴴ \nʾanya xa g-menxi b-aw [xet], \nma k-iʾe yimman zəlpa-la? ma k-iʾe yimman...? \ng-emer ruven mÉ™rre, \ngo ləbbe, ʾoha, \nk-xašwen ʾaxoni-le. \nču-xa la-k-iʾe yalunkəd mani-wax, ʾoha k-iʾe yalunkəd mani-wax ma? \nBA: mÉ™hÉ™m... \nSZ: ʾaz ʾaya wela xa naqla xet selu ham ʾuzle ʾọṭọ, \nnaqəl ṭḷa g-er mesu bənyame. \nzÉ™llu mÉ™rru ta babu,... \nbÉ™yame g-ebe. \ng-emer la-g-yawÉ™nne bÉ™nyame. \ng-emərre ʾo-hənna yē... yehuda g-er ʾətli tre bnone, \nway laši tlesele g-emer kutru zbuḥlu ʾakan la mə-seli bənyame ṭalox ṣax. \ng-emer way way wi qam-qaṭlətti! \nma bnone didox ma bnone didi?! \nBA: á´´naxon,á´´ \nSZ: wā̄y! qay mərrox hadxa?! \nqam-yawÉ™lele bÉ™nyame, \nzəlle, drele ᴴmalʾaxᴴ drele,... \nkašiyat qŭdduš dide go tera, \nu-ṭḷaha naqle zəllu u-selu, \nkulla k-iʾəttula, qam-pasxila, \nmpəqla kəz bənyamən, g-er bənyamən b-yawətule ṭali, \nʾaxtoxun b-ʾazetun bala bənyame. \ng-É™mri la g-ezax. \nb-ozax ᴴməlḥama,ᴴ \nb-hajməxla məṣṣər!\nqəmle yehuda g-emer ʾana b-hajmənna məṣər, \ng-emÉ™r hÉ™nna Ä\"... \nflankas ē psox hadxa u-bevankas ʾor bəd-do kolana, u- \nkullu ʾaxawase, \nÅ¡É™mÊ¿on u-levi u-... \nu-zxaryahu É™ zxarxaru, \nu-ʾamnonu, \nu-ʾaw xeta, \nkullu k-iʾannu šəmmae dohun, kud tre-ʾsar. \nha[w]e ᴴbriim,ᴴ kud tre-ʾsar. \nʾaz zəllu b-ḥalu. \nqam-ṣarəxlu, \nʾəfrayim, \ng-emÉ™rre,\nkela kaÅ¡iyÉ™t qudduÅ¡ didi wal gniwaloxun,  [g-]mer lex gniwe dida,  \nṭʾelu ṭʾelu xzelu wele go ṭʾ̣ẹṇet bənyame g-er bənyame ṭali-le. \nxa naqla tre u-ṭḷaha ᴴmalʾaxᴴ dəryale, \ng-er maxerwənna, yehuda g-er ʾo sepa maxənne atta axxa,\npalgəd məṣər maxərwənna. \nxzele tre mÉ™zze dide, \ne ʾoha rsuxlu, \nmaxru xa duka yosef. \ng-emer ta menaše u-frayim bnone dide, g-er xpuqule ʾo... \ndraun ʾizoxun [rə]š-kape, \nkullu wariḍe dide b-yatwi. \nqam-xabqile qam- hadxa ʾuzlu hădxă, \ng-emer wāy! ʾanya ʾizasa ʾiz[e]d be-babi-lu, \nBA: bes be babi,| \nSZ: ...nḥqlu ʾəbbi. \nsele g-er, žnid yosef, glele ṣaṣit dide, ṭàllis, \ng-er la-maxəwetun besoxun, ʾana ʾaxonoxun. \nqam-jamʿilu kullu, ʾuzlelu... \nʾuzlelu ʾixala ᴴtov,ᴴ našše u-efrayim zbəḥlu ʾərba, \nmutúlu qamu, xəllu, g-er šuqule bənyame, b-yanoxun taxte-rawan ʾəmed dəhwa.\nbabi drawle, băle ʾo ᴴkutonetᴴ didi hallula ṭale, \nwele maʿzul ʾay tre-ʾsar šənne, \nxamsa-ʾsar šənne. \nšayipla bəd ʾene, ʾene bahri. \nu-lÉ™Å¡lele kasme, \nbəd ʾize, u-qteʾle ḥəlla ʾəllu, \ng-er hallu ta babi ʾaxel mbarex ʾəllu.\nʾanya selu ž-ʾena, welu maḥkoye, \ng-əmri ʾo atta kefan sele u-... \nnablaxni ta baban u-yosef ʾaxonan wele ṣax, \nmani šmeʾla? \nmani šmeʾla? \nBA: ᴴʾem... ma-šma ʾos lo ʾosnat ʾe,ᴴ \nSZ: laʾ! \nBA: ʾàšer, brat ʾašer. \nSZ: šmeʾla brat ʿašer, əl hənna, seraḥ \nBA: ma-yle šəmm? seraḥ brat ʾašer! \nSZ: seraḥ brat ʿašer wela ž-ṃạya məndela kadduna, \nʾrəqla sela. \nʾaxona-le go dodiya,\nʾiza məndela g-əmra lae lae lae, \nxud rešəd ʾamoyi yosef d-ile ṣax go məṣrayim!\ng-emer xayet sawoe, xa-gar-xet mərra, mosa ʾəllax la-ha[y]e!\nxa-gar-xet mÉ™rra lae lae xud reÅ¡ s... \nmo moše a hənna yosef ʾamoi d-ile ᴴmelexᴴ go məṣrayim, \ng-er mosa ʾəllox la-ha[y]e.\nu-selu kullu drelu, hullule, hÉ™nna u-drele... \nʾene bhərru,\npəšla ᴴsəmḥa u-sason,ᴴ \nžnŭt qəmlu, moṭʾənnu, zəllu, hullelu ᴴʾer[eṣ]-gošen,ᴴ \nkullu qam-ʾawəzlu ḥakome u-wazire, \nmad muvṭəḥle ṭalu. \ng-er kulloxun b-ozənnoxun ḥakome u-wazire. \ntulu šəw-ʾasar šənne go məṣṣər, \nšəw-ʾasar šənne tulu go daw besa - go dan bate, kud xa u-bese. \nxarae, \nyaʿkov ʾavinu, \nžəlle, \nmboqəšle mən-ʾilaha g-emer, \ng-mesi go kolane naÅ¡e, ya rÉ™bono Å¡el Ê¿olam, \nhallu ṭḷaha yome peši ᴴḥolim,ᴴ\ng-er mÉ™nox Å¡kÉ™lla. \nxzele xa yome qÉ™mle, \nlewe ᴴmargiš ṭov,ᴴ \ng-er yehuda si-mesile yosef yatu xazri, barquli. \ng-er mesulu, šoʾi ᴴnexadimᴴ ʾətli, u-ᴴninim,ᴴ \nkullu matwulu, kullu tulu čaraxa, brone dide kud tre-ʾsar, \nbaxtasu, kullu tulu. \ntulle yosef ṭḷaha yome, \nxazer babe, reÅ¡e, \nʾize rəž reš babe, u-kullu yalunke. \ng-er broni drawuli š-kozənne nabluli ʾəl ē hənna, wela qora didi l-tama, ʾel e ḥəvron. \nmən məṣrayim b-ʾaqle bəd kozənne, l-ḥevron.\nkma-[h]ila? ʾe ḥuqosa-la dălăltă. \nBA: he, dalalta,\nSZ: ᴴʾammiti,ᴴ \nBA: ᴴbemetᴴ ʾeha la k-yanna ʾọṭọ, \nSZ: ʾo ᴴʾamiti,ᴴ\nBA: he,\nSZ: selu, tulu, \nbabu dre go hÉ™nna, \ntaxte rawan,\nṭṛelu, selu.\nselu wele ʿesav, g-emer la gə-mnablətule. la qorŭttule.\nʾana la qablena. ʾaxone hile go xa kasa-lu.\nᴴtəʾom dide hile.ᴴ\nqəmle naftali bər ʾə...\ná´´nexed did yehuda.á´´ \nbÉ™r brone.\nxapča ʿarj weale/ʿarja-le.\ng-er ʾo mani-le la qabəle ... nablaxle? \ng-əmri ʾo hənna-le, ʿesav ʾaxone hile,\nmorə́mle ʾize,\ntraq, mxele xa naqla ʾəl-qzalale,\nraḥqa mən axxa, reše qṭeʾle, \ngr gr gr gr gr zəlle xe ʾaqel d-yaʿakov.\nʾaz reše, \nzkele, ʾətle go ᴴmaʿarat maxpela,ᴴ\nʾətle xa ᴴḥederᴴ zurta,\nʾay ᴴrəšonaᴴ wele gawa.\nʾan xeta kullu welu go... \ngo ᴴḥeder.ᴴ\nBA: á´´yafe!á´´ \nSZ: ʾeha ʾaxoni-le kulle məḥkya dida  ᴴmila...ᴴ\nBA: ʾe la yʾeli kulla, \nSZ: ᴴmila be-milaᴴ ṭali.\nwela go reÅ¡i. \nhadxa-la g-əbe naša, yaʾe. \nBA: á´´naxon.á´´ \nSZ: fahem, xa mən ʾaw-xeta, kulla mi[n] ʾilaha. \nʾana ʾe ma-k-iʾan, u-ʾakan la məḥkya ṭali la k-iʾanwa ču-məndi. \nBA, OA: á´´naxon, naxon.á´´ \nSZ: ᴴʾavalᴴ\ndoqanwale maḥqoye dide, did hənna...\nyaḷḷạ!\nla xəlloxun ču-məndi la šteloxun! \nBA:  xÉ™llan\nʾeha,| dəd e məṣwa hila,\ná´´ve-ze haya nehedar.á´´ \nSZ: ʾatta mərrali, yala qam-xazyanne, \nmÉ™rri-la á´´barux ha-Å¡em, beseder,á´´ he.\nBA: á´´yofi, yofi, yofi.á´´ \nSZ: yaḷḷạ ᴴše-yihye laxem tov,ᴴ\nBA: á´´Å¡e-tizki le-harbe [yamim tovim]á´´ ','SZ: Have I told you [the story] of Yosef the Righteous?\nBA: No,\nSZ: When he went, when he came out of... \nHis brothers put him...\nBA: In the pit,\nSZ: In this, in the pit. They say \'We shall not ki-,\' one says we shall kill him [and] one [=the other] says we shall not kill him, [eventually] they did not kill him.\n[He] was put into the well, but that coat of him had torn [lit. was made one tear]. \nThey soaked it in blood, [and] took it to his father.\nBut his father knew he was not killed.\nHe did not... make a [period of] mourning for him.\nThat coat, one snippet/piece [of it] remained with him.\nSo when the merchants of Egypt came,\nthey [they brothers] say: \'we have one boy, young man, for sale,\'  \nThey [the merchants] say [=answer]: \'we will buy him\'.\n[When] they have bought him, he says: \'For God\'s sake take me to Rachel my mother, \n[in order that] I shall visit her, her tomb.\nIt is [on] your way, Beth-Lehem.\nFrom Jerusalem, from the field, they took him to Beth-Lehem.\nSo when he went to Beth-Lehem, - they all have been\nmerchants full [of], full [of] money, they carry property[/wealth] and goods\nthey sell [it] in Egypt.\nHe went [and] entered he says, he cried out a voice to his mother, in Kurdish [=Aramaic],\nHe says: [singing] \'Oh Mother! Rise and look at me [=see the poor condition I am in],\noh Mother! Rise and look at me!\nHere, on my leg there are chains,\n[???] on my hands,\nropes are placed on my legs,\nI have been sold to my owners,\nI have been sold to my owners.\'\nA voice came from his mother, all of the men shivered,\nthe grave of his mother shook, \nall of the people trembled.\nA voice came from his mother,\nhe [the voice] cried out: \'Oh my son Yosef, do not fear,\noh my son Yosef, do not fear,\nthree times, oh my son Yosef, do not fear,\ntrust in your God,\nWherever you go, you shall win [or: In the place that you go to, you will win],\nyou shall become the king of Egypt,\nyou shall become the king of Egypt.\nBA: That is so beautiful,\nSZ: She had said those [things], [and] those merchants,\nthen [or: immediately] untied his legs, \nreleased him [of his chains], saying as long as he has this mother, \nwhy [???] why did we tie him so [harshly]?\nThey untied him, he visited his mother, they sat down [and] sat him down [and] went away. \nThey brought his to Egypt,\n\'We have a boy for Egypt!\',\nPotipar came [and] bought him. \nPotipar does not have children,\nhe has taken Osnat [=Asenath] the daughter of Dinah,\nBA: Yes,\nSZ: from the field when Yaakov our Father begot her. \nThey have tied her in a hammock, \nthey named her [lit. put her name],\neh this,\nOsnat.\nUnder/after Osnat [???].\nPotipar was wandering around, hunting [lit. was turning around], [at].\nHe heard xwa qwa qwa a voice crying, he says \'Oh! [May I be] Your sacrifice, God, you have given me a daughter\'. \nHe put for her... a Turkish delight was in her mouth and he took her away.\nHe brought her up, Yosef also came [to Egypt] fourteen year old, \nalso he.\nBoth of them at the same night...\nbecame pregnant.\nRachel, this, Leah brought [some] sa_ad_ke [=a Kurdish vegetable which represent here the mandrakes] to her sister, \nBA: Yes,\nSZ: She [Leah] took the sa_ad_ke, [and] said to her \'Swallow those two, also I, but,\nfor the past fifteen days Yaakov has been with me,\nnow he is [=he should be] your guest, but tonight give him to me until ten o\'clock\'.\nShe said to Yaakov \'Go tonight again to my sister Leah.\'\nHe Says \'Why? I should be with you\', she says \'No, Go.\'\nHe went away, so she made a Din Ve-H_e_bon,\nshe went outside, after he had gone to he house,\nShe says: \'Oh Ruler of the universe, oh Ruler of the universe, I have six sons,\nif you give me a [an other] son, give this son to my sister Rachel,\n[and] give the daughter to me.\nI need one daughter.\nSo he came - the Ruler of the universe sent an angel,\nhe [the angel] said \'He [God] had accepted your plea [lit. the plea, He accepted it from you], \n\'You have made Din Ve-H_e_bon with the Creator of the universe, \nyou have a daughter in your womb, name her [lit. put (her name on) her]\nDinah, you have done Din Ve-H_e_bon with the Holy One blessed be He,\nher name is Dinah.\nBA: Yes,\nSZ: and a son will also come to Rachel, his name is [=should be] Yosef.\'\nBA: Yes,\nSZ: Here, this is their story, \nBA: Good,\nSZ: By brother is the one who told it to me.\nBA: Yes, I have never heard it [before],\nSZ: So the two of them, she gave birth to a daughter, Leah,\nRachel gave birth to a son,\nSo, um...\nThey came to Shchem,\nthey had already left [lit. went out \nfrom] Laban.\nYaakov our father had sat [=dwelled] [there], enough,\nhe wants to come to his Jerusalem.\nHe came, - he came to Shchem, he had a house in Shchem.\nThey kidnapped her, Dinah,\nHamor son of Shchem kidnaped her,\nson of Shchem.\nBA: Yes she was very beautiful,\nSZ: Yes,\nThey kidnaped her, they searched after her for three days, [but] she was not found [lit. s not seen]. \nHis father came, the father of Hamor,\nShchem,\nhe says,...\nWe all shall be together [lit. with in one another],\nyour daughter is with us, and we will give [you] whatever you want,\nwe shall do this. Her brothers say \'Absolutely no!\nwe are twelve Jewish brothers,\nthey are Muslims, we will give the girl to Muslims?!\' \nHe says \'We have one condition to you: we will circumcise all of you,\nfrom small [=young] to big [=old].\n[If] you except [that condition] we will give our daughter.\'\nGo ahead, Shimon and Levi, fall upon [=attack],...\nShchem.\nEven also a month old child \nthey have cut.\nAll of them died, all of their sons died, the daughter remained [alive]. \n[When] they rose, there was [lit. is] not a single man [left] in Shchem. \nThey brought back their daughter.\nThat man [or: her husband; Hamor], they have also killed. I know it [=the story] all.\nSo she came...\nshe became pregnant,\nGod gave her a daughter, so they say \'How...?\' [=This is inappropriate, what shall we do?]\nShe was put inside [a room] for nine months,\nThey did not let even one human being know she was pregnant,\nuntil,\nthat day which she should have given birth/gave birth, labor pangs started [lit. came to her], she was taken to the field,\n[???, perhaps a verb from the noun xesa, = lying-in woman]\nHer mother stood [=acted as] [and]  \nHer father  made for her a hammock [cradle], he make for her an amulet, \nhe put it on her right shoulder, \nthe amulet,\nand... he put [wrote there] a [sacred] name [or: her name], [in order that] no bird, \nwill be able come near to that place,\nnor touch her or...  cause her harm, and not...\nNo one was able to come near her,\n[since] the name of Yaakov our father was with her. \nThat was that... [or: She was born...]\nShe went away, he [Potipar] took her, he brought her up, Yosef also came,\nso he had [so it came about that he had; lit. it became to him] a daughter and a son, \nPotipar,\nBA: Yes,\nSZ: So then his wife fell in love with [also: desired] Yosef,\nshe does...\nno, he cannot overcome her [lit. he cannot over her], he always tells her no and no and no and no and...\nShe grabbed him [and] pulled him from his back.\nShe tore all of his clothes from his behind,\n[he did] not...\nHe says \'Forever, you are my mother.\' \nHe did not looked at her.\nShe had torn his clothes. [But] she started shouting \'Potipar, come and see!\nYou have brought this [person], he came... He wants to sleep with her, that which is here.  \nHe says \'Alright, to the court.\' \nThey went to court.\nThey say \'Bring him [in], make him stand here. If it is from here [=from the front], his clothes are torn,\n[then] it is he who went and asked [to sleep with] her.\nIf they are torn from behind, it is she, not... [him].\nHe did not initiate any conflict with her [lit. He does not have any apprehension of her. =He was not to be blamed].  \nThey saw they were [torn] from behind, the clothes, all of them torn over here. \nThey say, \'Nevertheless, we will give him [a punishment of] two years,\nprison,\nBA: For [the sake of] her honour.\nSZ: Yes, for [the sake of] the honour of Potipar.\nThey gave him, [the punishment of] two year.\n[But] after that, in one instance, he have erred, \n[it was] him [who erred],\n[so] he stayed [in prison] another ten years.\nHe erred with um...\num...\nWhoever have dreamt [lit. was seeing] a dream used to come to him,\n- well he was a \"man of dreams\" wi, - \nso one [person] came... \nhe had seen in his dream, [this person] was imprisoned with him - He did no eat!\nYosef the Righteous did not eat food, he drank [only] water and bread. Bread there, and water he used to eat, ten years he stayed in prison. \nBread and water he ate, he did not [even] taste the food of...\nthe Egyptians.\nThey would bring him three plates/dishes [lit. three plates used to come], [but] he used to give it to this [person] and to this and to this...\nHe says [to them] \'I am satiated from [=thanks to] God. \nSo um, that...\nThis one this, one,\nhe was his baker,\none [=the other] was a winemaker/dealer.\nThat baker saw in his dream, he [=Yosef] tell him \'Tomorrow,\nat three o\'clock they will hang you.\nThat which is not here .\nYou [will already] be dead.\nThat winemaker/dealer, he tell him \'You will come back, you will stay,...\nunder the hand of the king, and... be well\'.\nBut, he erred in one thing, he told him [or: he erred by saying one word to him],\nhe says \'Remember me [at] that time\'.\nHe should not have said it!\nBA: God will remember.\nSZ: [He should have said:] Oh Master of the universe, put in his heart that he may remember me.\nHe erred.\n[May I be the] sacrifice of God, [He] caught on him [=did not approve, became angry for that], He says \'You will stay [there] another ten years\'.\n[So] it is [lit. those are] twelve years. [=this is how he stayed there twelve years] \nAfter that, only then [or: at last] at that time, the king saw in his dream,\nseven cows eating seven... \nthis...\nfat cows\neating,\nthin cow,  and seven stalks eating.\nHe saw [the dream], he went [and] say [lit. he says] \'I want one to come [and] solve my dream,\nwhat, what did I see in my dream? I do not know what did I see\'.\nSo then that winemaker/dealer remembered.\nHe says \'No one can solve it but that which is in the prison, his name is [lit. they call him] Yosef\'.\nThey went [and] he brought him.\nWhen they have brought him [from prison], [and] brought him in to the king,\nwhat did he say to the king?\nHave you read [it]?\nDo you know what did he say to the king?\nOA: Um... When they have asked him what was the solution?\nSZ: Yes, no.\nBA: No.\nSZ: When he has entered to him [=to the king\'s hall] what did he say?\nBA: All solutions belong to God.\nSZ: No, he said \'Peace be upon you!\'\nBA: Oh,\nSZ: The king rose and sat in his chair,\nHe says to him \'I speak [lit. know] seventy languages, this one I do not know.\nWhat is it?\' He says to him \'That is Hebrew.\nBA: Oh,\nSZ: This \"Peace be upon you\" is in Hebrew.\' \n\'Who are you?\' He says \'I am a Hebrew.\'\nBA: Mm...\nSZ: He said to him \'My seal ring is on your hand [=Here, I give you my ring] ,\nyou shall become a king,\nin Egypt,\nevery thing shall be under your hand [=you shall rule Egypt].\nWhat is [the solution of] my dream?\' He says \'This is how it has been, this is how it has been,\' He says \'Aha! \nyou shall become the king of Egypt.\'\nHe became a king,\nnow, a king should be put in a chariot with a horse,\nthey should drive him around the streets of Egypt, saying [=announcing] \'Hey, come see this [man]\'.\nThey took him bath house, he bathed and dressed in royal clothes and he put [on] a royal crown,\nthey put him in a chariot and drive him around, all of the daughters of the noblemen, what have you, \nwrote letters and threw them to him into,...\nhis chariot.\nThis one [=girl] says \'I want you\', that one says \'I want you\', that one says \'I want you\'.\nBut that certain Osnat, what does she have? She has nothing, she has this amulet of her father.  \nShe wrapped it... [or: rolled it up...]\nBA: A bazband is a bracelet?\nSZ: Bazband they call it,\nThis this, like a...\nit is made - not a bracelet,\nun, writ...\nthis of him, his name,\nBA: Written? Ah!\nSZ: Write...\nand wrapped in this, and made [into]...\nBA: and they put it here, yes, \nSZ: [They (impersonal)] put threads  onto it and tie it with [a piece of] cloth. \nBA: Yes.\nSZ: Its name is bazband.\nHe [Yosef] reads it and...\n\'It is a amulet of my father, and this is the name of father and this is the daughter of my sister,\nnow, who shall I go and marry?\nShe who threw [the amulet to me], that is the one.\'\nBA: Of course, of course,\nSZ: He says \'I want Asenath, the daughter of Potipar\'.\nSo they married [lit. blessed] her to him, she brought him [=gave birth to] Menashe and Ephraim,\nBA: That is beautiful,\nSZ: So afterwards they came, it came about,...\nHe tells him \'Well what, what shall we do, now that you became the king? [lit. what shall we do in order you become a king?] He [Yosef] answer \'These [coming] seven years will be [lit. are] good,\nAfter these seven years a famine [lit. high cost of living, dearth] will come,\npeople will not be able to find bread [lit. bread will not be find in/cought to people]\'. \nSo, he made [some] pits, filled them, blessed,\nAll of them grew out wheat at that very moment they were sown.\nBut what others made, rotted.   \nBA: Yes,\nIt has become full of worms [lit. worms became].\nSZ: Yes. At that very same time, his brothers came [to their father].\nYaakov our father sat down, they say to him \'Father,\nsmell in which there is, in which city there is\nthe smell of wheat\'.\nHe smelled [and] smelled, he says \'The smell comes from Egypt, \ngo to Egypt.\'\nI know all of it, all of the words, accurately, it is not in vain.\nBA: That is beautiful, yes.\nSZ: \'All of you, go to Egypt, \nbut my son,\n- [Each] one [of you] protect the other [and] God shall protect you, - [but] I will not give my son Benjamin.\n[Here] he is, on my knee.\nUntil I die, Binyamin is mine.\nYosef went away, will I now also be without Benyamin?\'\nSo he send them away,\nat the same time Yosef saw,\nwith this [thing] of his [=his goblet],\nhe watches [and sees], ten riders have arrived.\nThey divided themselves, every two, \nfive [of them], entered trough a [different] trail. \nHe sent [men] towards them, saying \'Bring them here.\'\nThey came, he says \'What are you looking for? Are you spies?\' They say \'No,\nwe are not spies, we came [in order] to take...\nwheat [from] here.\nWe do not have [any], our father has sent us.\'\nSo that\'s it. You know their story.\nOne time he made for them a meal,\n[and] in that very first time,\nwhen they have just entered, he says \'Two,...\nsix sons of Leah, shall sit here\'. \nHe prepared for them a table.\nBA: yes,\nSZ: \'Two [sons] of Bilhah, over there.\nTwo of um...\nBA: Zilpah?\nSZ: Zilpah, over there\'.\nHe set [lit. made] tables  for them.\nThem, they look at each other [lit. those, one looks at the other],\n\'How does he know our mother is Zilpah? How does he know who...?\'\nHe says, Reuven said,\nin his heart, \'This [person],\nI think he is my brother.\nNo one knows children of whom we are, this [person] knows children of whom we are, how come?\'\nBA: Mmm...\nSZ: So this was it [=this was what had happened]. They came once again, [and] he had also done the same. \n[On the] third time he says \'Bring Binyamin!\'\nThey went [away] [and] said to their father:\n\'He wants Binyamin\'.\nHe says \'I will not give Benjamin.\'\nHe says um, him... [lit. this this...] Yehudah says \'I have two sons,\'\nWoe! my body is craked [d-r-z?] sweat [d-_-s?], he says \'Slaughter both of them if I do [lit. did] not bring Binyamin alive to you\'. \nHe [Yaakov] says \'Woe! you have killed me! [by having said that]\nWhich are your sons, which are my sons?! [=your sons are as dear to me as mine] \nBA: True,\nSZ: Woe! Why did you say such [things]?!\'\nHe gave him Benjamin.\nAn angel/messeng-er went [and] put,...\nhis Kiddush goblet in the saddle bag [of Biyamin],\nand they went away and came back,\nYou know all of it. They opened it,\nit turned out at Benjamin[\'s bag]. He says \'You shall give Benjamin to me,\nyou shall go away without Benjamin.\'\nThey say \'We shall not go.\nWe shall fight [lit. make a war],\nwe shall destroy Egypt!\'\nYehuda rose [and] said [lit. he says] \'I Shall destroy Egypt.\' \nHe says this um...\n\'So-and-so go ahead, like that, and so-and-so enter through this street, and...\'\nAll of the brothers, \nShimon and Levi and...\nand Zecharyahu eh Zcharcharu,\nand Amnonu,\nand the other one...\nI know all of them, their names, all twelve [of them].\nMay they be well, all twelve [of them].\nSo they went [onwards] in their state [of belligerence].\nHe called them,\nEphraim,\nhe says to him\n\'Where is my Kiddush goblet? You have stolen it\'. He says \'We have not stolen it\'.\nThey searched [and] searched, they saw it was in the luggage of Benjamin. He says \'Benjamin shall belong to me [lit. is for me]. \nOnce, twice, and three times, the angel placed it [in Binyamin\'s bag],\nhe says, Yehuda says \'I will strike [with] this sward now [right] here,\n[and] destroy half of Egypt!\'.\nHe [Yosef] saw two of his [Yehuda\'s] hairs,\neh, they were boiling,\n[Yehuda is about to] destroy a [certain] place, Yosef [knew]. \nHe says to Menashe and Ephraim his sons, he says \'Embrace his, this...\nput your hands upon his shoulder,\nall of his veins will sit down [=settle down, calm down]\'.\nThey hugged him, they have- like that, they did like that,\nhe says \'Why! These hands are hands of my father\'s house,...\nBA: My father\'s house, \nSZ: ...that have touched me!\'\nHe came, he says, immediately then  Yosef uncovered his Tzitzit, Tallit, \n[and] said \'Do not destroy your house [=family], I am your brother\'.\nThey gathered all of them, they made...\nthey made good food,  Menashe and Ephraim slaughtered a sheep. \nThey served them [lit. they placed in front of them], they ate, he says \'Leave Binyamin alone, I will give you a royal coach [or: sedan chair] of gold,\nput my father [on it[, but [first] give him this coat of mine. \nhe has been deprived [of me] for these [past] twelve years,\nfifteen years,\n[so he would] rub his eyes with it [with the coat] [lit. rub it with his eyes], his eyes will light [he will regain his joy]\'.\nAnd he kneaded pastries for him,\nin his [own] hand, and he separated [the portion of] Challah  from them.\nHe says \'Give them to my father [so that] he shall eat [and] bless over them\'.\n\nthey say \'Well now we have rejoiced [lit. our joy came] and...\nwe will bring to our father [the good kews], and Yosef our brother is alive...\'\nWho has heard?\nWho has heard?\nBA: Um... What\'s her name? Not Osnat, eh,\nSZ: No!\nBA: Asher, the daughter of Asher.\nSZ: The daughter of Asher heard, about this [thing], Serah\nBA: What is her name? Serah the daughter of Asher!\nSZ: Serah the daughter of Asher was at [lit. upon] the fountain, she threw away the pitcher,\nshe ran [away and] came.\n[While] her brother is in the rocking cradle,\nshe threw her hand [to the cradle, (=rocked the cradle)] saying \'Lae lae lae,\nby the head of my uncle Yosef who is alive in Egypt!\'\n[Yaakov] says \'Life of grandpa [affectionate address] say it one more time, death shall not come onto you!\'\nShe said one more time \'Lae lae by the head of...\nMoshe eh... this, my uncle Yosef is a king in Egypt\'.\nHe says \'Death shall not come onto you\'.\nAnd [then] all of them came, they put, gave him... this and he put...\nHis eyes became bright/shined/lit [=he rejoiced, revived],\nthere was [or: there started] a great joy and celebration.\nAnd then they rose, load [the coaches], went, he [Yosef] gave them the land of Goshen,\nhe made out of all of them kings and ministers,\nas he had promised them [lit. what he promised to them].\nHe says \'I will make all of you kings and ministers\'.\nThey sat [=dwelled] seventeen years in Egypt,\nseventeen years they have dwelled in that house - in those houses, each one [of them] and his [own] house.\nAfterwards,\nYaakov our father,\nwent,\nasking of God, saying,\n\'people die in the streets, oh Master of the universe,\ngive them three days of illness [lit. that they be sick]\'.\nHe [God] says \'It shall begin with you [lit. it has begun from you]\'.\nHe saw one day, he woke up, \n[that] he does not feel well.\nHe says \'Yehudah go bring/fetch Yosef [so] he [shall] sit next to/near me, in front of me\'.\nHe says \'Bring them, I have seventy grandchildren and great-grandchildren,\nseat down all of them\'. All of the loiterers sat down, his sons, all twelve [of them].\nTheir wives, all of them set down.\nYosef sat [their] three days,\nnear to his father, near him [lit. upon],\nhis hands on his father\'s head, and all of the [other] children.\nHe says \'My son, put me on mules, carry me to this, my grave is there, in eh... Hebron\'.\nFrom Egypt by foot, by mules, to Hebron.\nHow much is it [=how far is it]? That is the fine precious story.\nBA: Yes, precious.\nSZ: [It is a] true [story],\nBA: Really. I did not know this one like that [lit. that I do not know like that],\nSZ: It\'s real.\nBA: Yes,\nSZ: They cam [and] sat down,\n[They] put their father in this...\nroyal chariot,\nthey rode away [and] came. \nThey came there was Esau, he says \'You will not take him through. You will not burry him.\nI do not permit/allow it\'. He is his brother, they were in a one [same] womb [how could he do that?]. \nHe is his twin brother.\nNaphtali of eh... rose, \ngrandson of Yehudah.\nThe son of his son.\nHe was slightly lame/had a small limp.\nHe says \'Who is he that do not allow... us to take him [Yaakov] [through]?\'\nThey say \'It is this [person], it is Esau his brother\'.\nHe raised his hands,\nTraq! He stroke once at his neck [lit. necks].\n[May it be] far away from here,  his head was cut off, \ngr gr gr gr gr it went [=rolled] under the foot of Yaakov.\nSo his head,\nwon this merit. It has, in the Cave of the Patriarchs, \nit has a small room,\nthe first [room], it [the head] is there [lit. in it].\nThe others [the Patriarchs and Matriarchs] are all in.. \nin [a separate] room.\nBA: Beautiful!\nSZ: This [story], my brother has told all of it, word...\nBA: I did not know all of it,\nSZ: word by word to me.\nIt is in my head.\nThis is how it is, a person should, know [=be knowledgeable].\nBA: True.\nSZ: [One should] understand. One from the other [=The stories and knowledge are passed on from one person to the other], [but yet] all of it is [=comes] from God.\nI, what do I know? And if he had not told me, I would not know/have known anything\nBA, OA: Right, right.\nSZ: But,\nI grasped [firmly] his sayings, of this... [of those stories, of Torah].\nYallah!\nYou have not eaten anything, you have not drunk.\nBA: We have eaten,\nthis, which is of a Mitzvah [some refreshments from a feast of a Brit Milah],\nand it was splendid.\nSZ: She has [just] now told me, \'I saw the child\',\nI told her \'Thank God, [every thing is] all right\', yes. \nBA: Good, good, good.\nSZ: Yallah, may [only] good happen to you.\nBA: May you merit [to live] many good days.\n',''),(175,'The King and the Wazir','A folktale told by Habbubba Masusani, daughter of famous Zakho storyteller Mamo Yona Gabbay.',78,'audio/The King and the Wazir.mp3',NULL,NULL,NULL),(176,'The Caliph, the Advisor and the Scorpion ','A folktale told by Habbubba Masusani, daughter of famous Zakho storyteller Mamo Yona Gabbay.',78,'audio/The Caliph, the Advisor and the Scorpion HM130107T3.mp3',NULL,NULL,NULL),(177,'The Daughter, the Pomegranate, and the Cat','A folktale told by Habbubba Masusani, daughter of famous Zakho storyteller Mamo Yona Gabbay.',78,'audio/The Daughter, the Pomegranate, and the Cat HM130107T5.mp3',NULL,NULL,NULL),(178,'The Three Nephews and the Three Cups','A folktale told by Habbubba Masusani, daughter of famous Zakho storyteller Mamo Yona Gabbay.',78,'audio/The Three Nephews and the Three Cups HM121217T7.mp3',NULL,NULL,NULL),(179,'The People of Zariwaw','In this recording, the speaker describes the community of Jews that used to live in Diyana prior to 1948. This text, as well as all other texts on Christian Diyana-Zariwaw have been published by Lidia Napiorkowska in \'The Christian Neo-Aramaic Dialect of ',80,'audio/Rahana.Bradusnaye.mp3','<span class=aramaic> 1) yĕ̀dat ʾaširat modlie?ˈ 2) rɒba mɒtwɒte ʾašìrat-in\'ˈ 3) ʾu-ʾaxni zaruwànayeˈ halbat… zaruwanaye… bradusnàyexˈ 4) bas bradusnaye süraye xàččewaˈ ʾɒtuṛaye xàččewaˈ 5) naheyat… ʾo mǝ́nṱaqa ṱ-amrila bradusnàyeˈ ʾǝč̣č̣i ʾu-ṱḷa mɒtwɒ̀tewaˈ 6) ṱḷa mɒtwɒte bas ʾitwa ʾɒtuṛàyeˈ ṣìruˈ ʾu-riččàwaˈ ʾu-zarìwawˈ 7) bas zariwaw trè batewa…ˈ tre mahallàt-iwaˈ mɒta ḷḷètaˈ ʾu-mɒta xtètaˈ 8) [LN: bas ʾaxtün lètün Gargarnaye?] 9) la ʾaxni lèx jarjarnayeˈ làˈ lèx jarjarnayeˈ 10) bas xəzmǝd ʾǜdaḷex ʾaxni ʾu-jarjarnayeˈ 11) nàra ʾit nobandanˈ ʾit nàra nobandanˈ</span>\n\n','1) Do you know what a tribe is? 2) Many villages form a tribe. 3) And we, the people of Zariwaw, perhaps... the people of Zariwaw... we are the people of Baradost. 4) But (among) the people of Baradost the Assyrians were few, the Assyrians were few. 5) The governo... this area that they call it the (tribe) of Bardost was ninety-three villages. 6) Three villages only were Assyrian: Ṣiru and Riččawa and Zariwaw. 7) But Zariwaw was two households... it was two neighbourhoods: the upper and the lower village. 8) [LN: But you are not the people of Gargar?] 9) No, we are not the people of Gargar, no, we are not the people of Gargar. 10) But we are each other\'s cousins, we and the people of Gargar. 11) Between us, there is a river, there is a river between us.',''),(180,'Agricultural life in Surka','The informant, Dinkha d-Kufa, who was born in Hesherke and grew up in Surka talks about the agricultural life in Surka.',163,'audio/Dinkha Sliwo Sawmo.mp3',NULL,NULL,NULL);
